but also kind of a fear, what if I don't have what it takes, you know? I lost sleep. So this

03:03:02.520 --> 03:03:07.800
was one consequence of this. I, for the first time in my life, I had trouble falling asleep. And

03:03:07.800 --> 03:03:12.520
this actually stayed for a couple of years afterwards. So then it was kind of like a wake-up

03:03:12.520 --> 03:03:17.400
call that I should be to take care of myself, not work too late and so on. So that was sort of like

03:03:17.400 --> 03:03:22.920
that experience. And I was lucky that I was able to find a solution, number one, within two months,

03:03:22.920 --> 03:03:28.600
maybe. And it was very, it was surprising and it was beautiful. Like it, the answer was, was in

03:03:28.600 --> 03:03:33.000
terms of some, something which seemed to be from a different world, from a different area of mathematics.

03:03:33.000 --> 03:03:40.840
So I was very happy. But I do remember this moment when suddenly you see that. Just like

03:03:42.040 --> 03:03:47.320
in this case, it was literally, I had to compile these diagrams with what mathematicians call

03:03:47.320 --> 03:03:53.880
cohomology groups and spectral sequences and manually calculate some numbers and trying

03:03:53.880 --> 03:03:59.880
to discern some system in it. And suddenly I saw that how they all were governed by this one,

03:04:00.440 --> 03:04:06.200
one force, so to speak, one pattern. And that was absolutely, wow. So it's like...

03:04:07.320 --> 03:04:09.640
Maybe what was it? So you're sitting there at a desk?

03:04:10.360 --> 03:04:15.000
Actually, you know, I lived in a town outside of Moscow. So I used to take, I would take a train

03:04:15.000 --> 03:04:19.080
to Moscow. So it's what we call in Russia, electric, you know, like this electric train,

03:04:19.080 --> 03:04:23.640
which was super slow. It took more than two hours to cover that distance. And I think that

03:04:23.640 --> 03:04:29.480
the crucial insight came when I was in this. And I just, I had to contain myself so I don't

03:04:29.480 --> 03:04:36.760
start screaming, you know, because there were other passengers in the car. So I was sitting there

03:04:36.760 --> 03:04:44.120
and staring at this paper. So you know what? I remember that's what came to me. I have something

03:04:44.120 --> 03:04:50.040
now, which nobody else in the world has. I have a proof of... First of all, it was not just a proof.

03:04:50.040 --> 03:04:54.200
Like in the case of Fermat, the statement is already made. That's why it's called conjecture.

03:04:54.200 --> 03:04:58.680
You know, you make a statement, you don't have a proof yet. Then you try to prove it. In my case,

03:04:58.680 --> 03:05:03.720
I did not know what the answer would be. There was a type of question where the answer was unknown.

03:05:03.720 --> 03:05:09.080
So I had to find the answer and prove it. And the answer was very nice. So nobody knew, as far

03:05:09.080 --> 03:05:14.760
as I could tell, nobody knew because my teacher told me that he explored all the literature. And

03:05:14.760 --> 03:05:23.800
this was not known. So this was... Suddenly I felt that I was in possession of this. Now,

03:05:23.880 --> 03:05:29.880
it was a little thing. It was not cure for cancer. It was not a large language model.

03:05:31.160 --> 03:05:38.840
But it was something undeniably real, meaningful. And it was mine kind of. I had it, nobody else.

03:05:38.840 --> 03:05:45.240
I had not published it. I didn't even tell anybody. And it is a very strange feeling to have that.

03:05:45.240 --> 03:05:47.720
Were you worried that this treasure could be stolen?

03:05:48.680 --> 03:05:53.080
Not at the time. Not at the time. So later on, there were situations where

03:05:53.080 --> 03:05:57.160
I was exposed to those types of experiences. But at that time, I didn't think of that. I was

03:05:57.160 --> 03:06:05.000
still this starry-eyed kid who was just obsessed with mathematics, with this beauty and discovering

03:06:05.000 --> 03:06:11.400
those beautiful facts, beautiful results. So I didn't even think that it could be possible

03:06:11.400 --> 03:06:16.120
that somebody could steal it or whatever. I just wanted to share it with my teacher as soon as

03:06:16.120 --> 03:06:21.400
possible. And he understood quickly. And he's like, good job.

03:06:22.840 --> 03:06:29.240
Is there something you can give color to the drama? Eric Weinstein has spoken about

03:06:29.240 --> 03:06:34.120
some of the challenges, some of the triumphs and challenges of his time at Harvard.

03:06:37.640 --> 03:06:44.280
Is there something to that drama of people stealing each other's ideas or not allocating

03:06:44.360 --> 03:06:50.920
credit enough? Oh, sure. Yes. All of that and creating psychological stressors because of that.

03:06:50.920 --> 03:06:54.840
Happens all the time, yes, unfortunately. On young minds and so on.

03:06:54.840 --> 03:06:58.840
Could have a very bad effect. Is that just the way of life or is this...

03:07:00.760 --> 03:07:04.920
I think we can definitely do better. And I think the first step is to kind of

03:07:05.720 --> 03:07:12.760
admit that we are not 100% seekers of truth, that we are human beings and all the

03:07:13.720 --> 03:07:23.080
good and bad and the ugly qualities can be present and to have some kind of dialogue

03:07:23.080 --> 03:07:28.760
in my subject, in mathematics. This has not happened yet. There have been some famous cases

03:07:28.760 --> 03:07:33.880
where people have been accused, which had been resolved or partially resolved or unresolved.

03:07:34.680 --> 03:07:39.480
And everybody knows it, but there isn't a systematic effort, as far as I can tell,

03:07:40.360 --> 03:07:45.800
of really trying to create some rules, some ethics rules. This is fair game,

03:07:45.800 --> 03:07:52.120
this is not fair game, so that as a community, we strive to get better. I think that for most

03:07:52.120 --> 03:07:57.400
people it's more like keeping your head in the sand and kind of pretending that it doesn't happen.

03:07:57.400 --> 03:08:02.360
Or it happens some isolated incidents. Well, my experience is not like that at all.

03:08:02.360 --> 03:08:06.440
I think it does happen much more often than it should. That's my opinion.

03:08:07.400 --> 03:08:12.680
So there's the pool of academia is fascinating. One of the reasons I really love it is you have

03:08:12.680 --> 03:08:19.400
young minds with fresh ideas. And that same innocence you had when you first on the train

03:08:19.400 --> 03:08:24.040
have that brilliant breakthrough. And then you throw that in together with senior,

03:08:24.680 --> 03:08:29.960
exceptional world-class scientists who have, first of all, are getting older.

03:08:30.200 --> 03:08:40.280
Second of all, maybe they have partaken in the drug of fame and money and status and recognition.

03:08:40.280 --> 03:08:47.080
So that starts to a little bit corrupt all of our human minds. And you throw that mix in together.

03:08:48.600 --> 03:08:55.320
Mostly without rules. And it's beautiful because that's where the ideas of old

03:08:56.280 --> 03:09:03.640
contend with the new wild-eyed crazy ideas and they clash and there's a tension and there's

03:09:03.640 --> 03:09:08.600
a dance to it. But then there's the old human corruption that can take advantage of the young

03:09:08.600 --> 03:09:14.040
minds. It's unclear what to do with that. I mean, part of that is just the way of life

03:09:14.040 --> 03:09:20.120
and there's tragedies. And oftentimes when you look at who wins the Nobel Prize, it's also tragic

03:09:20.760 --> 03:09:27.480
because sometimes so many minds are, the trajectory to the breakthrough idea

03:09:28.040 --> 03:09:31.480
involves so many different minds, young and old. Yeah, I mean,

03:09:35.000 --> 03:09:42.760
you're right. I think it's like everything else. The path is to more self-awareness.

03:09:42.760 --> 03:09:49.240
And that's like owning up your own stuff and not blaming other people, not projecting onto other

03:09:49.240 --> 03:09:56.520
people, but taking responsibility. And that's true for everything. And the problem here,

03:09:56.520 --> 03:10:01.560
unique problem for mathematics, I would say thesis and chemists are better. They actually

03:10:01.560 --> 03:10:06.200
have better sort of ethical rules and so on, especially biologists. Because I think in part

03:10:06.200 --> 03:10:09.880
it's because there is much more money involved, because they have to get grants and so on. So

03:10:09.880 --> 03:10:14.120
for them, the question of priority, who discovered what first is much more serious because there's

03:10:14.280 --> 03:10:18.280
really some serious money. Mathematics, who cares? You know, like Fermat's last theorem was proved.

03:10:18.840 --> 03:10:22.440
Did Andrew Wiles become a millionaire? No. I think he got a prize.

03:10:22.440 --> 03:10:29.160
He won a prize, but those prizes are not... I think that one was a big prize, but in general,

03:10:29.160 --> 03:10:33.080
there's not going to be... I think he won the Nobel Prize, eventually, which is about a million

03:10:33.080 --> 03:10:40.440
dollars. But sometimes I joke about this, that this is the hardest way to win a million dollars.

03:10:41.400 --> 03:10:51.000
So, you know, but amongst mathematicians, I think the trouble is that we are so insulated

03:10:52.920 --> 03:11:00.840
from society because it's such a pure subject. It draws in very specific psychological types.

03:11:01.480 --> 03:11:06.200
And I can speak about myself. I did not realize it at the time, but later on, I definitely saw...

03:11:07.000 --> 03:11:12.120
I mentioned some of it earlier, that for me, mathematics was a refuge from the cruelty of

03:11:12.120 --> 03:11:16.680
the life I experienced, from discrimination that I experienced when I applied to Moscow University

03:11:16.680 --> 03:11:21.240
at 16, being failed at the exam and stuff like that, which I describe in my book as well. But

03:11:23.000 --> 03:11:28.200
that was my way. I was like, I don't trust this world. I don't want to deal with it.

03:11:28.920 --> 03:11:35.880
I want to hide in this platonic reality of pure forms. This is where I know how to

03:11:35.880 --> 03:11:43.000
operate. I love this, and I couldn't be bothered in some sense. For a while, up to a point, as I was

03:11:43.000 --> 03:11:49.240
getting older and more mature, I was becoming more and more interested in other things. But I think

03:11:49.240 --> 03:11:56.920
that's one of the reasons. And one of the reasons why I wrote Love and Math was precisely to break

03:11:56.920 --> 03:12:04.840
that cycle. That it's the quiet guy in the corner that goes into math, and not the flamboyant, you

03:12:04.920 --> 03:12:15.320
know, jock or like, you know, DJ. I wanted to show how beautiful the subject is to attract this new

03:12:15.320 --> 03:12:25.000
blood so that different psychological types and more women would join. Because then they would

03:12:25.000 --> 03:12:30.440
have the students who would look at them and whom they will inspire. And then it would be...

03:12:31.320 --> 03:12:35.880
Instead of a vicious circle, it would be a virtuous circle. And I have to say, I think it's

03:12:35.880 --> 03:12:39.960
happening not because of my efforts alone. Obviously, there are many other mathematicians

03:12:39.960 --> 03:12:46.040
who are around the same time started to put more effort. Because see, if the old stereotype of

03:12:46.040 --> 03:12:50.840
mathematician, you're so enclosed, you're not interested in even exposing the beauty of your

03:12:50.840 --> 03:12:55.800
subject to other people, you see? And then it becomes this vicious circle. But you know, this

03:12:55.800 --> 03:13:02.360
one day, you know, all the time I meet the students who say, your book is the reason why

03:13:03.080 --> 03:13:08.120
I chose Math as my major. And I am proud, especially when it's women who tell me this.

03:13:08.120 --> 03:13:14.760
And they are cool. They are DJs at the same time. And they are social. And they have friends.

03:13:14.760 --> 03:13:20.280
And they go out and so on. You see, so then they carry the torch. Because then they will be more

03:13:20.280 --> 03:13:28.840
likely to share this beauty with others, to attract more students and so on. So I think this

03:13:28.840 --> 03:13:33.880
kind of this dumb was broken. So now you have more influx. And once we have people who are more

03:13:34.520 --> 03:13:40.120
able to connect at the personal level, that's when we also become more self aware as a community,

03:13:40.120 --> 03:13:45.560
I think. And that's when we might be, we should be able to have a chance to improve in terms of

03:13:45.560 --> 03:13:52.600
our ethical rules and stuff like that. So let me return to our friend Eric Weinstein for a question

03:13:52.600 --> 03:13:57.560
that I would ask anyway, but let me let's have a non Russian ask the Russian question.

03:14:00.280 --> 03:14:05.800
Ask him about the Russian concepts of friendship, science, gender and love versus the American.

03:14:06.040 --> 03:14:14.920
You can. So there is a there is a deep romanticism that you have

03:14:17.080 --> 03:14:25.320
that runs to your book, Love and Math. Is part of that something you've picked up from the Russian

03:14:25.320 --> 03:14:33.320
culture? What can you speak to that fueled both your fascination with math and your fascination?

03:14:33.320 --> 03:14:39.160
No, your your prioritization of the human experience of love.

03:14:40.600 --> 03:14:47.400
Good question. I definitely there is some influence of the Russian culture, Russian literature,

03:14:47.400 --> 03:14:53.560
perhaps, you know, but also, you know, like, there's so many things. How do you how do we develop

03:14:53.560 --> 03:14:58.680
certain sensibilities? Like, why do we care about this and not that? Like, why do I care, for instance,

03:14:58.760 --> 03:15:05.160
about, like you said, about this romantic ideal, so to speak of mathematics? That's certainly not

03:15:05.160 --> 03:15:09.720
something that is automatic. You know, some people care about some people don't. And I'm not saying

03:15:09.720 --> 03:15:15.160
it is superior or inferior. It's just how my composition, my psychological composition is like

03:15:15.160 --> 03:15:22.680
that. And it's an interesting question, like, what is the cause of it? So I think that

03:15:22.840 --> 03:15:29.160
we cannot really know, but there are some aspects of it, of course, the experiences life experiences

03:15:29.800 --> 03:15:39.080
are bringing family, like I was, you know, I was surrounded by love by my parents on the one hand,

03:15:39.080 --> 03:15:46.440
but in the other side, perhaps they were a little overprotective of me. So I was kind of like, you

03:15:46.440 --> 03:15:55.160
know, too much kind of like taking taking care of so then when I develop certain sensitivity,

03:15:55.160 --> 03:16:00.760
but I was kind of not ready for the challenges of the real world of the real world. So then that

03:16:00.760 --> 03:16:07.560
that struggle and that and then being lost and then being able to overcome and to learn. And

03:16:08.280 --> 03:16:15.320
then if you do, you know, if you don't lose, you don't appreciate maybe, but sometimes when

03:16:15.880 --> 03:16:20.040
we lose something and then regain it, then we cherish it, we appreciate and then becomes

03:16:20.040 --> 03:16:29.080
unimportant. Also, various difficulties, you know, the upsetting experiences or one could say

03:16:29.080 --> 03:16:35.560
traumatic experiences growing up, you know, in the Soviet Union, that was not a walk in the park,

03:16:35.560 --> 03:16:44.520
you know, there were a lot of issues there that I had to go through. And and then it doesn't break

03:16:44.520 --> 03:16:53.800
you make you stronger. But in my case, what happened was that, you know, some for some of it,

03:16:53.800 --> 03:16:57.960
it took me 30 years to really come to terms with it and to really understand what happened.

03:16:59.320 --> 03:17:07.320
It gave me this motivation to to strive to become a mathematician, which maybe I wouldn't

03:17:07.320 --> 03:17:12.360
have otherwise it charged me supercharged me. I'm talking about, for instance, I experienced with

03:17:12.440 --> 03:17:16.440
exam at Moscow University. Can you take me through that experience?

03:17:16.440 --> 03:17:25.240
So this is 1984. We spoke about Orwell earlier. And I was applying to Moscow University

03:17:27.080 --> 03:17:33.800
mathematics department called Mehmet, which is like for people who don't know, like the place

03:17:33.800 --> 03:17:38.760
was the only place to study pure mathematics in Moscow period. But also, but also if you want

03:17:38.760 --> 03:17:43.320
the great places on earth. And it's like a huge building, this, you know,

03:17:44.280 --> 03:17:53.240
this monolith of a building of Moscow University. So because, as I said, you know, a year earlier,

03:17:53.240 --> 03:17:58.040
Evgeniy Evgeniy, which converted me into math, capitalizing on my love for physics, quantum

03:17:58.040 --> 03:18:03.240
physics. And so we spent a whole year studying with him. And I was really kind of at the level of,

03:18:04.200 --> 03:18:09.880
you know, in some in some subjects, the level of like early graduate graduate studies.

03:18:10.760 --> 03:18:18.040
So it seemed like it would be a breeze to get into Moscow University. But in fact, little did I know

03:18:18.040 --> 03:18:27.480
that there was a policy of antisemitism where students like me would be failed by special

03:18:27.560 --> 03:18:35.480
examiners, mostly during the oral exam with mathematics, but occasionally I would be written

03:18:35.480 --> 03:18:43.240
tests and stuff. Now, my father is Jewish by blood. It was not religious. His family was not

03:18:43.240 --> 03:18:49.560
religious. My mom is Russian. And but I was since my last name was my father's name. So it was very

03:18:49.560 --> 03:18:56.680
easy to to read what my nationality was. And so there was this, can you imagine, there were

03:18:56.680 --> 03:19:02.520
special people who would screen up applicants who would put aside the files of the undesirables.

03:19:03.400 --> 03:19:06.840
There would be special examiners who were actually professors at this university

03:19:07.720 --> 03:19:14.280
who would be designated as those who would take the exam from those undesirables.

03:19:15.000 --> 03:19:20.200
It was it's almost comical when you look back now. And also like questions why there was no

03:19:20.200 --> 03:19:24.600
reason other than just hatred of the other. That's how I see it. It's just to give a little bit

03:19:24.600 --> 03:19:32.520
more color. So because you mentioned nationality, it's a little quirk that perhaps gives an insight

03:19:32.520 --> 03:19:37.400
to the bigger system that the nationality listed on your birth certificate when you're Jewish is

03:19:37.400 --> 03:19:42.680
Jewish. And when you're non-Jewish, is this as Russian for me, it was Russian. So first of all,

03:19:42.920 --> 03:19:48.920
in the inner part, everybody has an internal passport. And there you have first name,

03:19:48.920 --> 03:19:57.240
pateranemic name, last name, date of birth. So these are four. And the fifth colon is nationality,

03:19:58.920 --> 03:20:02.760
which comes from the nationality of the parents and so on. In my case, it was written Russian

03:20:02.760 --> 03:20:09.480
because my mom was Russian, but it didn't save me because I was my dad's last name.

03:20:10.280 --> 03:20:17.320
And so anyway, this was the toughest experience that I had up until that point.

03:20:18.600 --> 03:20:24.600
And there was this two people who came into the room where I was the only undesirable. All other

03:20:24.600 --> 03:20:30.520
kids were being questioned by other examiners, but they told me that we cannot question you.

03:20:30.520 --> 03:20:37.080
We are waiting for special examiners. So I was like, oh, oh, something is food. And so these

03:20:37.080 --> 03:20:41.800
two guys came in four hours, basically, were asking me questions, which were not in the

03:20:41.800 --> 03:20:45.560
program and so on. But I was like, yeah, I was 16 years old. I tried to answer it best I can,

03:20:45.560 --> 03:20:51.800
but it was a setup. It's been documented since then, there are even lists of problems

03:20:52.680 --> 03:20:59.560
that were given to undesirables in those days. In my year, no Jewish applicants,

03:20:59.560 --> 03:21:05.240
as far as I know, Jewish by this metric were accepted. So then I had to go to this.

03:21:07.480 --> 03:21:12.680
There was one technical school in Moscow, which was the Institute for Oil and Gas Exploration,

03:21:13.240 --> 03:21:22.040
which had applied mathematics program. And that's where many of the kids who were not

03:21:22.040 --> 03:21:31.800
accepted to Moscow University ended up. But the point is, and then I was so motivated by this,

03:21:31.800 --> 03:21:39.560
because I wanted to show those guys that within five years, less than five years,

03:21:39.560 --> 03:21:44.840
I got a letter from the president of Harvard University inviting me as a visiting professor

03:21:44.840 --> 03:21:50.520
to Harvard. I was 21, I was barely 21, because I already did some research in the meantime.

03:21:51.080 --> 03:21:57.160
That's how motivated I was. But the interesting aspect of it is that

03:21:59.240 --> 03:22:04.760
for the longest time afterwards, I was telling myself a story that nothing really happened.

03:22:05.960 --> 03:22:12.120
It wasn't so bad. Okay, so I was failed, but I knew that I was going to succeed.

03:22:13.480 --> 03:22:19.960
It was 30 years later that I finally got to meet that boy, that 16-year-old.

03:22:20.520 --> 03:22:28.440
That I neglected this time. And I realized that he died, that it was a crashing blow.

03:22:28.440 --> 03:22:29.080
The innocence?

03:22:29.800 --> 03:22:34.360
Not just the innocence, because there was no way. It looked like there was no way I could become

03:22:34.360 --> 03:22:41.880
a mathematician, because if they don't accept me there, it's over. I didn't know that I could

03:22:41.880 --> 03:22:47.960
actually find this striving applied math program, and then eventually somebody would take me under

03:22:47.960 --> 03:22:52.760
his wing and so on, and then could move to the United States. That was not in the realm of

03:22:52.760 --> 03:22:59.480
possibilities. So there was nothing to look forward to. It was clear that it's over. I cannot

03:23:02.120 --> 03:23:13.640
do what I love. And so when I finally connected to that boy, oh my God, I was a totally different

03:23:13.640 --> 03:23:21.720
experience. All the pain and all the trauma came to the surface. And it was a kind of a tsunami.

03:23:22.520 --> 03:23:28.840
I wasn't sure I would survive this. It was so hard. And what happened was I was invited to

03:23:30.200 --> 03:23:34.520
give a talk about this in New York. It was kind of a spoken word event

03:23:36.600 --> 03:23:41.160
about science, but like personal experiences related to science. This was almost a year after

03:23:41.960 --> 03:23:48.520
my book came out. In my book, one of the first chapters is a chapter about this experience.

03:23:49.640 --> 03:23:53.240
But what I realize now is that I wrote it from the third person perspective.

03:23:53.960 --> 03:23:58.520
I knew the facts, but I was not emotionally connected to that experience. However,

03:23:59.080 --> 03:24:04.520
since I wanted to write the book and to connect to my readers, I allowed the boy to write it.

03:24:05.560 --> 03:24:10.280
So a lot of people were touched by it, and people would say, wow, that chapter, you know,

03:24:10.360 --> 03:24:14.520
it really got a lot of resonance. It was translated into another language even before the book was

03:24:14.520 --> 03:24:21.560
published. I was surprised by this because I didn't know yet. So the adult Edward was not

03:24:21.560 --> 03:24:31.560
yet in touch, but the book gave the outlet to the child. And that kind of started the process.

03:24:32.360 --> 03:24:41.080
So finally, almost a year later, I'm in New York in this event. And the night before,

03:24:42.360 --> 03:24:46.440
I'm in my hotel room, and I was like, okay, what am I going to talk about tomorrow?

03:24:46.440 --> 03:24:50.600
And I take a piece of paper just to, you know, my usual preparation, you know, for things.

03:24:51.800 --> 03:24:55.800
And then suddenly I have this vision that I will walk up to the microphone tomorrow,

03:24:55.800 --> 03:25:06.520
and I will just start crying. And I was like, by that time, I already had an insight

03:25:06.520 --> 03:25:12.360
